======================================================================
PART 1: THE PETERSEN DECOMPOSITION — PENTAGON + PENTAGRAM
======================================================================

Petersen K(5,2):
  Vertices (10): [(1, 2), (1, 3), (1, 4), (1, 5), (2, 3), (2, 4), (2, 5), (3, 4), (3, 5), (4, 5)]
  Edges (15)

  (1, 2): neighbors = [(3, 4), (3, 5), (4, 5)]
  (1, 3): neighbors = [(2, 4), (2, 5), (4, 5)]
  (1, 4): neighbors = [(2, 3), (2, 5), (3, 5)]
  (1, 5): neighbors = [(2, 3), (2, 4), (3, 4)]
  (2, 3): neighbors = [(1, 4), (1, 5), (4, 5)]
  (2, 4): neighbors = [(1, 3), (1, 5), (3, 5)]
  (2, 5): neighbors = [(1, 3), (1, 4), (3, 4)]
  (3, 4): neighbors = [(1, 2), (1, 5), (2, 5)]
  (3, 5): neighbors = [(1, 2), (1, 4), (2, 4)]
  (4, 5): neighbors = [(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 3)]

  Every vertex has degree 3 (3-regular)
  Girth (shortest cycle) = 5 (pentagon)
  Diameter = 2 (any two vertices at distance ≤ 2)

  Number of 5-cycles (pentagons): 24
  Number of 6-cycles (hexagons): 20

  Independent set counts by size:
    size 0: 1 independent sets (empty set)
    size 1: 10 independent sets
    size 2: 30 independent sets = h(E₈)!
    size 3: 30 independent sets = h(E₈)!
    size 4: 5 independent sets = α(P) = rank(F₄)

  Independence polynomial I(P,x) = 1x^0 + 10x^1 + 30x^2 + 30x^3 + 5x^4
  Note: coefficients include 30 at both x² and x³!

======================================================================
PART 2: FIVE PLATONIC SOLIDS ↔ FIVE EXCEPTIONAL LIE GROUPS
======================================================================

  The McKay correspondence (extended):
  Solid                     Group    |G|  Lie  r   dim   h
  ------------------------- -------- --- ---- -- ---- ---
  Tetrahedron               A₃/T      12  E₆   6   78    12
  Cube/Octahedron           B₃/O      24  E₇   7   133   18
  Dodecahedron/Icosahedron  H₃/I      60  E₈   8   248   30

  But there are 5 exceptional Lie groups, not just 3!
  The 'missing' two: G₂ and F₄

  ALL 5 EXCEPTIONAL LIE GROUPS:
  Type  rank  dim   h     |W|          det  Platonic connection
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  G₂    2     14    6     12           1    Dihedral D₆ (hexagon)
  F₄    4     52    12    1152         1    24-cell (self-dual 4-polytope)
  E₆    6     78    12    51840        3    Tetrahedron (via BT)
  E₇    7     133   18    2903040      2    Cube/Octahedron (via BO)
  E₈    8     248   30    696729600    1    Dodec/Icos (via BI)

  G₂: the 'hidden' exceptional — related to OCTONIONS
    G₂ = Aut(O), the automorphism group of the octonions
    dim(O) = 8 = rank(E₈), dim(G₂) = 14 = 2·rank(E₇)

  F₄: the 'middle' exceptional — related to JORDAN ALGEBRA
    F₄ = Aut(J₃(O)), the automorphism group of 3×3 octonionic Hermitian matrices
    dim(J₃(O)) = 27 = KEY₂³ = dim(V_E₆)

  PROPOSED 5↔5 CORRESPONDENCE:

  Platonic Solid    ↔  Exceptional Group  ↔  Petersen Feature
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Tetrahedron (4V)  ↔  E₆ (rank 6)       ↔  4 = α(Petersen)
  Cube (8V)         ↔  E₇ (rank 7)       ↔  8 = rank(E₈) link
  Octahedron (6V)   ↔  G₂ (rank 2)       ↔  6 = h(G₂) = E(tetra)
  Dodecahedron(20V) ↔  E₈ (rank 8)       ↔  20 = f(7) = V(dodec)
  Icosahedron (12V) ↔  F₄ (rank 4)       ↔  12 = h(E₆)=h(F₄)

  This correspondence is NON-STANDARD but note:
    V(tetra) = 4 = rank(F₄) = α(Petersen)
    V(cube) = 8 = rank(E₈)
    V(octa) = 6 = h(G₂)
    V(dodec) = 20 = f(7)
    V(icos) = 12 = h(E₆) = h(F₄)
    Total: 4+8+6+20+12 = 50 = 2·25 = KEY₁·(KEY₁+KEY₂)²

======================================================================
PART 3: THE GOLDEN RATIO AS PETERSEN EIGENVALUE RATIO
======================================================================

Golden ratio φ = (1+√5)/2 = 1.6180339887

Petersen eigenvalues: λ₁=3, λ₂=1, λ₃=-2
  λ₁ = KEY₂ = 3
  λ₂ = 1
  λ₃ = -KEY₁ = -2

Ratios and golden connections:
  λ₁/|λ₃| = 3/2 = KEY₂/KEY₁ = 1.5
  φ² = φ+1 = 2.6180339887
  φ² = 2.6180339887 ≈ KEY₂-φ+1 = 2.3819660113... no

φ in the icosahedron:
  Icosahedron vertices include (0, ±1, ±φ) and permutations
  Edge length = 2 = KEY₁ (for unit circumradius)
  The ratio of diagonal to edge in a regular pentagon = φ

THE PENTAGON-PENTAGRAM IN PETERSEN:
  The outer ring of Petersen is a 5-cycle (pentagon)
  The inner ring is a 5-cycle (pentagram)
  Cross edges connect outer to inner

  Pentagon diagonal/side = φ = 1.6180339887
  Pentagon: 5 vertices, 5 edges
  Pentagram: 5 vertices, 5 edges
  Cross edges: 5
  Total: 10 vertices, 15 edges
  = V(Petersen), E(Petersen)

THE NUMBER 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂ divides:
    10 = V(Petersen)
    15 = E(Petersen) = C(6,2)
    30 = h(E₈) = E(dodec) = E(icos)
   120 = |Aut(P)| = |S₅| = |BI|
    60 = |A₅| = icosahedral rotation group
    20 = V(dodecahedron) = f(7)
    5  = # exceptional Lie groups
    5  = # Platonic solids
    5  = # regular star polygons ({5/2})

======================================================================
PART 4: THE PENTAGON-PENTAGRAM DUALITY AND E₈ LATTICE
======================================================================

E₈ LATTICE AND ICOSIANS:

  The E₈ lattice Γ₈ can be constructed from icosians:
  Icosians = quaternions a + bi + cj + dk where a,b,c,d ∈ Z[φ]
  The 240 shortest vectors of E₈ = the 120 icosians (doubled)

  Binary icosahedral group BI ⊂ S³:
    |BI| = 120 = |S₅| = |Aut(Petersen)|
    BI has elements of orders: 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 10
    The orders {1,2,3,4,5,6,10} all divide 60
    60 = 2·30 = 2·h(E₈)

  BI elements by conjugacy class:
      2 elements: ±1                        (order 1,2)
      6 elements: ±i,±j,±k                  (order 4 (cube vertices))
     16 elements: (±1±i±j±k)/2              (order 3,6 (24-cell/BT))
     24 elements: φ-icosians                (order 5,10 (dodec+icos))
     72 elements: mixed φ-icosians          (order assorted)
    Total: check = about 120 (exact grouping varies)

  PETERSEN ↔ E₈ LATTICE:
    Petersen complement has 30 = h(E₈) edges
    These 30 edges ↔ the 30 positive roots in a rank-4 subsystem
    V(Petersen)=10 ↔ 10 = dim(so(5)) = dim(sp(4))
    The 2-element subsets of {1,2,3,4,5} that form Petersen vertices
    are the same indexing as so(5) basis elements e_ij (i<j)

======================================================================
PART 5: S₅ ACTING ON THE DOUBLE-5
======================================================================

S₅ acts on K(5,2) by permuting the ground set {1,2,3,4,5}:
  |S₅| = 120 = |Aut(K(5,2))| = 5! = |BI|
  S₅ acts transitively on vertices (single orbit)
  S₅ acts transitively on edges (single orbit)

  Key subgroups of S₅:
  Group        |G|  Description        Lie connection
  S₅           120  Full Aut             E₈ (|BI|)
  A₅            60  Even perms           Icos rotation
  S₄            24  Stabilizer of a point E₆ (|BT|)
  D₅            10  Dihedral             V(Petersen)
  Z₅             5  Cyclic               Rotation of pentagon
  S₃             6  3-element perms      h(G₂)
  S₂×S₃         12  2+3 partition        h(E₆)=h(F₄)
  Z₂             2  Swap two             KEY₁

  The index [S₅:S₄] = 120/24 = 5 = KEY₁+KEY₂
  The index [S₅:A₅] = 120/60 = 2 = KEY₁
  The index [S₅:D₅] = 120/10 = 12 = h(E₆)
  The index [S₅:Z₅] = 120/5 = 24 = |BT|
  The index [S₅:S₃] = 120/6 = 20 = V(dodec)

  BEAUTIFUL: the indices of S₅ subgroups give tournament/Lie data!
  120/2 = 60  120/5 = 24  120/6 = 20  120/10 = 12  120/24 = 5
  = |A₅|      = |BT|     = V(dodec) = h(E₆)     = KEY₁+KEY₂

======================================================================
PART 6: THE KNESER GRAPH SEQUENCE K(n,2)
======================================================================

Kneser graphs K(n,2): vertices = 2-subsets of [n], edge = disjoint

    n  V=C(n,2)         E    deg     χ     α  notes
    4         6         3      1     2     3  K₃ (triangle)
    5        10        15      3     3     4  PETERSEN! f(10)=56=T(6)
    6        15        45      6     4     5  
    7        21       105     10     5     6  rank(E₇)! V=21=21=C(7,2)
    8        28       210     15     6     7  
    9        36       378     21     7     8  
   10        45       630     28     8     9  
   11        55       990     36     9    10  

  K(5,2) = Petersen is the smallest Kneser graph that is NOT a complete graph
  K(4,2) = K₃ (complete graph on 3 vertices)
  The Petersen graph is the BOUNDARY case — the moat!

  TOPOLOGICAL SIGNIFICANCE (Lovász's proof):
    χ(K(n,r)) = n - 2r + 2  (Lovász 1978)
    For K(n,2): χ = n - 2
    K(5,2): χ = 3 = KEY₂ (needs 3 colors)
    The proof uses the Borsuk-Ulam theorem!
    Borsuk-Ulam: f: Sⁿ→Rⁿ has antipodal point with f(x)=f(-x)
    This is TOPOLOGY forcing COMBINATORICS.

======================================================================
PART 7: THE 5-FOLD SYMMETRY BREAKING CASCADE
======================================================================

Starting from 5 = KEY₁ + KEY₂, the cascade breaks symmetry:

Level 0: The number 5
  5 = KEY₁ + KEY₂ (the sum of keys)
  5 is the largest prime where (2,3,p) is spherical
  5 is the dimension where simplex packing gives |BI|=120

Level 1: 5 → {2, 3} (additive splitting)
  KEY₁ = 2: controls parity, binary structure
  KEY₂ = 3: controls ternary structure, triangulations
  Together: z² - 5z + 6 = 0 (characteristic equation)

Level 2: 5 → 10 (doubling)
  10 = 2·5 = V(Petersen)
  The double-5: pentagon + pentagram
  f(10) = 56 = T(6) = dim(V_E₇)

Level 3: 5 → 30 (tripling by KEY₂, or 2·3·5)
  30 = h(E₈)
  φ(30) = 8 = rank(E₈)
  The 30-edge trinity: icos, dodec, J(5,2)

Level 4: 5 → 120 (factorial)
  120 = 5! = |S₅| = |BI| = |Aut(Petersen)|
  = number of simplices tiling a 5-cube
  = order of icosahedral group

Level 5: 5 → 240 (doubling of 120)
  240 = #roots(E₈) = 12·20 = V(icos)·V(dodec)
  = 2·120 = 2·|BI|

  The cascade in powers of keys:
    5                    = KEY₁+KEY₂
    10 = 5·KEY₁          = KEY₁(KEY₁+KEY₂)
    30 = 5·KEY₁·KEY₂    = KEY₁·KEY₂(KEY₁+KEY₂)
    120 = 5·KEY₁³·KEY₂  = KEY₁³·KEY₂·(KEY₁+KEY₂)
    240 = 5·KEY₁⁴·KEY₂  = KEY₁⁴·KEY₂·(KEY₁+KEY₂)
    720 = 5·KEY₁⁴·KEY₂² = KEY₁⁴·KEY₂²·(KEY₁+KEY₂) = 6!

======================================================================
PART 8: α=4 AND THE 4 NON-E₈ EXCEPTIONALS
======================================================================

The Petersen graph has independence number α = 4
  A maximum independent set has 4 vertices
  There are 5 maximum independent sets

  Maximum independent sets (5):
    ((1, 2), (1, 3), (1, 4), (1, 5))  union = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
    ((1, 2), (2, 3), (2, 4), (2, 5))  union = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
    ((1, 3), (2, 3), (3, 4), (3, 5))  union = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
    ((1, 4), (2, 4), (3, 4), (4, 5))  union = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
    ((1, 5), (2, 5), (3, 5), (4, 5))  union = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

  Each max independent set has 4 vertices (pairs).
  Their union covers all of {1,2,3,4,5}

  4 = α(Petersen)  ↔  4 non-E₈ exceptionals:
    G₂ (rank 2, dim 14)
    F₄ (rank 4, dim 52)
    E₆ (rank 6, dim 78)
    E₇ (rank 7, dim 133)

  For each max independent set of size 4:
    Remaining 6 vertices form the 'dependent core'
    6 = h(G₂) = KEY₁·KEY₂
    The dependent core has 6 vertices = h(smallest exceptional)

  Clique number ω(Petersen):
    ω = 2
    Max cliques: 15
      ((1, 2), (3, 4))
      ((1, 2), (3, 5))
      ((1, 2), (4, 5))
      ((1, 3), (2, 4))
      ((1, 3), (2, 5))
      ((1, 3), (4, 5))
      ((1, 4), (2, 3))
      ((1, 4), (2, 5))
      ((1, 4), (3, 5))
      ((1, 5), (2, 3))

  ω(P)·α(P) = 2·4 = 8
  Compare: V(P) = 10
  So ω·α = 8 < V = 10
  Ratio V/(ω·α) = 5/4

======================================================================
GRAND SYNTHESIS: THE DOUBLE-5 AS ORGANIZING PRINCIPLE
======================================================================

The Petersen graph K(5,2) is the DOUBLE-5:

  OUTER PENTAGON (5 vertices)  ↔  5 Platonic solids
  INNER PENTAGRAM (5 vertices) ↔  5 exceptional Lie groups
  15 EDGES                     ↔  C(6,2) = T(5) via 12-edge complement
  30 NON-EDGES                 ↔  h(E₈) = Coxeter number

  The 5+5 = 10 vertices partition as:
    α = 4 (max independent set) → 4 non-E₈ exceptionals
    10 - α = 6 (dependent core) → h(G₂) = smallest Coxeter #

  Eigenvalues {3, 1, -2} = {KEY₂, 1, -KEY₁}:
    Positive eigenvalues: 3+1 = 4 = α
    Negative eigenvalue: |-2| = 2 = KEY₁
    Sum: 3+1+(-2)·... wait
    Eigenvalue sum (with mult): 3·1 + 1·5 + (-2)·4 = 3+5-8 = 0 ✓ (traceless)

  Spectral decomposition: Tr(A) = 0
    3(1) + 1(5) + (-2)(4) = 3 + 5 - 8 = 0
    Multiplicities: 1, 5, 4
    1 = unit
    5 = KEY₁+KEY₂ (the double-5 generator)
    4 = rank(F₄) = α(Petersen)

  THE PETERSEN GRAPH IS THE ROSETTA STONE:
  It translates between combinatorics (tournaments),
  geometry (Platonic solids), algebra (Lie groups),
  and topology (Borsuk-Ulam/Lovász theorem).
